<br>
Two points that I'd make to Verant both involve the issue of &quot;making the game fun.&quot;<br>
<br>
1) When the alternate experience system was first introduced, i was really proud of Verant.  Instead of having 10 really tedious grind levels, they had 100 relatively-short &quot;levels&quot; where you could get rewarded after each one.  By increasing the amounts of &quot;rewards&quot; that could be achieved, they made the game more fun and less boring.   By nerfing the alt xp system, they made it more like 100 boring levels.  This makes the game &quot;less fun.&quot;  It was a bad idea.<br>
<br>
2) The one mitigating factor to this was AE grouping.  Jyll's spells are great spells.  They're made for dishing out fast damage to almost unlimited targets.  Being able to pull 10, 20, 30 mobs at once and use our AE spells was great fun, and allowed us to achieve the ingame rewards of alternate advancement.<br>
<br>
My argument to the folks at VI is that -- by nerfing the Grey -- they once again made the game &quot;less fun.&quot;  <br>
<br>
I'd honestly suggest that the game designers think about &quot;what makes a game fun&quot; -- not just profitable or addictive or time requiring.  Grinding, monotonous, pull-one-at-a-time grouping certainly doesn't fit my definition of fun.  People are much more likely to stop sending VI their $10/month because of boredom due to NON-advancement, than because they've gotten all 100 skill points and there's now nothing left to do.<br>
<br>
Somewhere along the line, VI has lost sight of what makes a game fun.<br>
<br>
--Tremas Trueheart (Baron!)<br>
Sorcerer of Vazaelle<br>
&lt;Promethian Order&gt;<br>
